commentPostTextItems.html: That's all we have for this game. Ireland have some serious worrying to do and need to pull up their socks before the ODI series too begins to slip away from them. Plenty of time to stage a comeback, though, as there are four games remaining. Afghanistan's unstoppable run this tour continues and they will head into the second ODI on Friday with a world of momentum and confidence. See you then. Until then, it's good bye from us. Thank you for joining us.
Baher : "Congratulation Afghanistan Every hard work has joyful result. "

Asghar Stanikzai - Every series, the first game is very important. Porterfield and Stirling played very well. Credit goes to Rashid Khan and Dawlat Zadran and it proved to be a very good comeback. The old ball is good for reverse swing and Dawlat is an experienced bowler which is capable of reversing it. That's why the game opened.

Porterfield - It's frustrating that the century did not come in a winning cause. We thought we wer ein a great position, but they never gave up and this is a game we should have won. We had a good partnership but we knew it wasn't going to be easy. We should have had a couple more partnerships to see it off. I think he played a couple of good knocks in the T20s and got a 60-odd in the previous game. So not too worried about the form of the middle order.
William Porterfield is the Man of the Match for his century.

5.20pm What a collapse this has been! Ireland were cruising and you thought they would perhaps finish this with five overs to spare. The game still got over with 19 balls to spare, just that the result wasn't quite what Ireland were hoping for. And it is that man - Rashid Khan - who did it again, with four wickets. Good support from Dawlat Zadran who also chipped in with four wickets. If you have just tuned in, Ireland were 206 for 2 in the 36th over. And from there, it has been a collapse of some proportions. Ireland's forgettable tour continues after being swept in the T20s and Afghanistan go 1-0 up. Stay tuned for the presentations.

commentPreTextItems.html: Fazalrabi : "Ireland aren't giving up that easily. conceded 25 runs in the last three overs. It isn't yet finished. "

dismissalText.commentary: Mohammad Shahzad run out (KJ O'Brien) 43 (41b 7x4 1x6) SR: 104.87

dismissalComment.html: could be run-out here, third umpire has been called for. Pushes it into the leg side, to the right of midwicket who runs across, picks up and fires at the non-striker's end in one smooth motion. The replays show he was ambling across lazily. There was some doubt with the bowler's hands being close to the stumps, but the third umpire has seen enough to conclude that O'Brien's throw broke the wickets

dismissalComment.html: he's picked the fielder. Arm ball, angled in at off stump, he hangs back, gets low and wants to slog this through midwicket. But it skids on quickly, his bat turns and he picks out short midwicket who takes it low under his eyes. Wasn't to the pitch of the ball and that shot is difficult to pull off on this pitch if you aren't

dismissalComment.html: lazy shot. Good length outside off, very slight movement away, but it's his lack of feet movement that has done him in, not the ball's. Pokes at it a couple of yards outside the off stump, gets an outside edge through to the keeper

dismissalComment.html: ...and that was the shot of a tired man as well. dismissalText.commentary: William Porterfield c Samiullah Shinwari b Dawlat Zadran 119 (98b 18x4 0x6) SR: 121.42

dismissalComment.html: he's chipped it to extra cover! Full ball outside off, looks like it has stopped on him as he goes for to cover drive again. dismissalText.commentary: Kevin O'Brien st †Mohammad Shahzad b Amir Hamza 13 (19b 1x4 0x6) SR: 68.42

dismissalComment.html: gone. Superbly done. Oh, what a delivery. He was backing away to make room and the bowler fires it flat, lack of flight and on a length. He comes forward and looks to flick it away but the ball spins away from him and he ends up walking into the shot. Shahzad does the rest

dismissalText.commentary: Gary Wilson lbw b Dawlat Zadran 0 (1b 0x4 0x6) SR: 0

dismissalComment.html: and another! Trapped right in front. Good length, swinging in slightly again, pitches and skids off the pitch, straight at leg stump. Wilson rooted to his crease, nervously tries to get bat on it but doesn't manage to. Up goes for the finger

dismissalText.commentary: Stuart Thompson c sub (Shafiqullah) b Dawlat Zadran 2 (7b 0x4 0x6) SR: 28.57

dismissalComment.html: full and outside off, Thompson drives on the up but cannot place it well. Picks out mid-off who runs an inch or two to his left and snaffles it. Ireland in more than some trouble here.

milestones.description: Porterfield and Paul Stirling's 157-run partnership is IRE's highest for the 2nd wicket in ODIs, breaking the record of 153 between Eoin Morgan and Porterfield
This is the highest match aggregate (554) involving teams Ireland & Afghanistan in ODIs
Dawlat Zadran has broken the record for most ducks (5) in ODIs for AFG, going past Asghar Afghan's 5

stories.title: Dawlat, Rashid fire Afghanistan to fighting win
stories.subTitle: Afghanistan v Ireland, 1st ODI, Greater Noida
stories.seoTitle: Dawlat Zadran, Rashid Khan bowl Afghanistan to fighting win
stories.summary: Dawlat Zadran and Rashid Khan took four wickets each as Ireland faltered from a dominant position in a chase of 293 to concede the first ODI to Afghanistan by 30 runs
